7. Univariate plots of columns: 'rating', 'Age', 'release year', 'Gender' and 'Occupation¶

In [31]:
# Univariate plot for age

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
plt.title('Univariate Analysis - Age Distribution')
sns.distplot(User_Data['age'],color='gold'); # plots a histogram
plt.axvline(User_Data['age'].mean(), color='R', linewidth=2,label='Mean')
plt.axvline(User_Data['age'].median(), color='K', linewidth=2,label='Median')
plt.axvline(User_Data['age'].mode()[0], color='B', linewidth=2,label='Mode')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

age is positively skewed. Mean is greater than Median and Mode¶

8. Visualize how popularity of genres has changed over the years¶

In [44]:
# Creating new dataframe by copying  Movie_Data Dataframe- 
# Apply groupby and make 'release year' as index and 'all genres' as columns 
# Apply sum() to get the number of movies released per genre in a year and dropping other columns

Genre_temp=Movie_Data.copy()
Genre_Popularity=Genre_temp.groupby('release year')[Genre_temp.columns].sum()
Genre_Popularity.drop(columns=['release year','movie id'],axis=1,inplace=True)
Genre_Popularity.tail()
